Here is a code snippet that could be used to seed the pseudo-random function from the true-random ADC:

```
int cc2538_random_read(uint8_t *outEntropy, size_t inSize)
{
    uint32_t            randword; 
    unsigned char       *pbuf           = outEntropy;
    const size_t        req_words       = inSize >> 2;
    const unsigned char *pbuf_end       = outEntropy + inSize;
    const unsigned char *preq_words_end = 
      (unsigned char *)(((uint32_t *)outEntropy) + req_words);
    ptrdiff_t           remainder_bytes = pbuf_end - preq_words_end;

    for (pbuf = outEntropy; pbuf < preq_words_end; pbuf += 4)
    {
        HWREG(SOC_ADC_ADCCON1) |= 0x00000004;
        randword = HWREG(SOC_ADC_RNDL) | (HWREG(SOC_ADC_RNDH) << 8);
        memcpy(pbuf, &randword, 4);
    }

    if (remainder_bytes)
    {
        HWREG(SOC_ADC_ADCCON1) |= 0x00000004;
        randword = HWREG(SOC_ADC_RNDL) | (HWREG(SOC_ADC_RNDH) << 8);
        memcpy(pbuf, &randword, remainder_bytes);
    }

    return 0;
}
```

@hubertmis I agree that this leads to unnecessary network load, but does it prevent the handshake from succeeding? 
The only time-agnostic remedy I could conceive on the level of Mbed TLS is to never issue multiple retransmissions in response to what the library finds within a single datagram, but this wouldn't solve the problem when multiple datagrams have accumulated during a longer calculation. 
In that regard, I also wanted to ask you and @erja-gp if your code performs some merging of datagrams in the receive buffer? Otherwise, I don't see how it could happen (using Mbed TLS) that a retransmitted `ChangeCipherSpec` and an `ApplicationData` message share the same datagram.

